icted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCurrent media and political discourse on crime has long ignored crimes committed by States themselves, despite their greater financial and human toll. For the past two decades, scholars have examined how and why States violate their own laws and international law and explored what can be done to reduce or prevent these injustices. Through a collection of essays by leading scholars in the field, State Crime offers a set of cases exemplifying state criminality along with various methods for controlling governmental transgressions. With topics ranging from crimes of aggression to nuclear weapons to the construction and implementation of social controls, this volume is an indispensable resource for those who examine the behavior of States and those who study crime in its varied forms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aPolitical crimes and offenses. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBarak, Gregg1 aBassiouni, M. Cherif1 aBohlander, Michael1 aChambliss, William1 aFriedrichs, David1 aHaveman, Roelof1 aHoofnagle, Kara1 aIadicola, Peter1 aKauzlarich, David1 aKramer, Ronald C.1 aMichalowski, Raymond J.1 aMullins, Christopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aParmentier, Stephan1 aRoss, Jeffrey Ian1 aRothe, Dawn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWeitkamp, Elmar08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813550237423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813550237.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015